The controller returns the output of `db[table_name].validate_and_insert(**vars)`. `.validate_and_insert` first runs the validators defined for each field and then does the insert only if there are no validation errors. If no record is inserted, this implies that there are validation errors.

Note, validation errors in this case do not automatically result in an exception or a non-200 HTTP response. Rather, the controller simply returns the output of `.validate_and_insert` (converted to JSON), which is a structure like:

    {
      id: [ID of inserted record if successful or null otherwise],
      errors: {
        &#39;field1&#39;: &#39;error message 1&#39;,
        &#39;field2&#39;: &#39;error message 2&#39;,
        ...
      }
    }

If you do not want a 200 response when there are validation errors, you can change the controller code to something like this:

        def POST(table_name,**vars):
            result = db[table_name].validate_and_insert(**vars)
            if result.errors:
                raise HTTP(422, &#39;INVALID INPUT&#39;)
            return result

Alternatively, you can return the result with a 200 response and have your client code inspect the returned JSON to determine if there were any validation errors and take action accordingly.

In either case, you should be prepared to handle validation errors when they occur.

